PDC220H1-F-20229.courseTitle: Arts & Science Internship Program - Maximizing Your Experience
PDC220H1-F-20229.courseDescription:
This course is a mandatory component of the Arts & Science Internship Program (ASIP) for students admitted to the ASIP stream of their program for Year 2, and students admitted for Year 2 must successfully complete this course and receive a passing grade to gain access to the ASIP job board. The course will provide an opportunity for students to prepare for and maximize their learning and personal development through ASIP. Topics may include: self-assessment – skills, values, interests; building a career and co-op plan; skills articulation – how to identify, articulate and apply skills gained through courses and other life experiences; personal marketing documents; guided self-reflection on barriers to employment; resources and toolkits to support access for all; and co-op student panels.

This course does not carry credit weight and is evaluated as Credit/No Credit. No tuition fee is associated, however an ancillary fee will be assessed. Refer to the ASIP Fees & Financial Aid website for further details.

Students who enrolled in the ASIP stream of their program in Year 3 should enrol in PDC230H1.
PDC220H1-F-20229.webTimetableInstructions:
The PDC220H1 course is available to all Year 2 students enrolled in the Arts & Science Internship Program and will include both synchronous and asynchronous components. Specific synchronous sections will occasionally have some subject matter tailored to specific disciplines. 

The following LEC sections will be tailored to the programs below: 

  • Monday 10am – 11am: Book & Media Studies, Industrial Relations & Human Resources, Pharmacology & Toxicology, and Pharmaceutical Chemistry
  • Wednesday 12pm – 1pm: Computer Science
  • Thursday 3pm – 4pm: Mathematics
  • Thursday 5pm – 6pm: Computer Science and Statistical Science

The synchronous PDC220H1 LEC sections will be taking place bi-weekly starting the week of September 26th, 2022.
PDC220H1-F-20229.deliveryInstructions:
This course will have online and in-person synchronous and asynchronous components. It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online programming.

Lecture section options include both online and in-person synchronous delivery formats.

PDC221H1-S-20229.courseTitle: Arts & Science Internship Program - Essential Skills for ASIP Success
PDC221H1-S-20229.courseDescription:
This course is a mandatory component of the Arts & Science Internship Program (ASIP) for students admitted to the ASIP stream of their program for Year 2, and students admitted for Year 2 must successfully complete this course and receive a passing grade before starting their first work term. The course will help students prepare for their first work term and optimize their chances of success in the first recruitment cycle. Topics may include: ASIP guidelines and requirements, resume and cover letter tailoring, professionalism essentials, job search essentials, interview preparation, workplace rights, health and wellbeing while in ASIP, and accessibility and EDI considerations.

This course does not carry credit weight and is evaluated as Credit/No Credit. No tuition fee is associated, however an ancillary fee will be assessed. Refer to the ASIP Fees & Financial Aid website for further details.

Students who enrolled in the ASIP stream of their program in Year 3 should enrol in PDC231H1.

The following LEC sections will be tailored to the programs below: 

  • Monday 5pm – 6pm: Computer Science and Statistical Science
  • Tuesday 12pm – 1pm: Mathematics
  • Thursday 10am – 11am: Computer Science
  • Thursday 1:30pm – 2:30pm: Book & Media Studies, Industrial Relations & Human Resources, Pharmacology & Toxicology, and Pharmaceutical Chemistry

The synchronous PDC221H1 LEC sections will be taking place bi-weekly starting the week of January 16th, 2023.

This course will have online and in-person synchronous and asynchronous components. It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online programming.

PDC320H1-F-20229.courseTitle: Arts & Science Internship Program - Professional Skill Development I
PDC320H1-F-20229.courseDescription:
This course is a mandatory component of the Arts & Science Internship Program (ASIP) for students admitted to the ASIP stream of their program for Year 2. Students admitted for Year 2 must successfully complete this course to graduate from the ASIP Stream of their program of study. The course will help students build transferable skills essential for success in the workplace and in the evolving world of work. The course will also support and help guide students through the next recruitment cycle. Topics may include: post work-term reflection (if applicable), advanced interview skills, job search support for recruitment cycle II, and skills development modules. Skills development modules may include: design thinking, communication, problem solving, conflict resolution, and ethical and sustainability-minded decision making.

This course does not carry credit weight and is evaluated as Credit/No Credit. No tuition fee is associated, however an ancillary fee will be assessed. Refer to the ASIP Fees & Financial Aid website for further details.

  • Tuesday 11am – 12pm: Mathematics
  • Wednesday 1pm – 2pm: Book & Media Studies, Industrial Relations & Human Resources, Pharmacology & Toxicology, and Pharmaceutical Chemistry
  • Thursday 1pm – 2pm: Computer Science

The synchronous PDC320H1 LEC sections will be taking place bi-weekly starting the week of September 19th, 2022.
